  <h1>About</h1>

  <div class="bio">
    <p>I'm Aneesh — a software engineer who writes about software, taste, and ambition. I grew up moving between things, and I built a career on the same instinct: shipping systems that are precise underneath and quiet on the surface.</p>

    <p>Most of my time goes to AI engineering. Retrieval, evals, the unglamorous plumbing that decides whether a model feels useful or feels like a parlor trick. I care about <em>what makes a system trustworthy</em> — not the demo, the third week of production.</p>

    <p>Outside the terminal, I'm watching a few things closely: materials and fashion-tech (the part of the future you can touch), deep tech and the capital flowing into atoms, and New York as the operating system I happen to run on. The throughline is the same one I look for in software — specificity, restraint, and a point of view.</p>

    <p>FALSE COLOR is a personal magazine. I made it because the usual portfolio template flattens the things I actually think about, and because I'd rather think out loud than rehearse. Issues come out when they're ready. Drafts stay drafts longer than they should.</p>

    <p>If any of that lands — or you think I'm wrong about something — <em>say so</em>. I read everything.</p>
  </div>

